 tEncore “All Things Reconsidered”: Reflections on Phish and Jewishness -- t13 “Yerushalayim Shel Zahav” Comes to Phish: An Interview with Shirley Halperin -- t14 Bringing Phish to the Holy Land: An Interview with Rachel Loonin Steinerman -- t15 Blessed by Bass: An Interview with Marc Brownstein -- t16 Becoming the General of Jam: An Interview with Jonathan Schwartz -- t17 Mike’s Corner Reprise: An Interview with Mike Gordon -- tAfterword -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhish has a diehard fan base and a dedicated community of enthusiasts—called Phishheads—who follow the band around the country, some fans attending every show. What may be surprising is that a significant percentage of Phishheads are Jewish.Two members of the band—bassist Mike Gordon and drummer Jonathan Fishman—were raised in Jewish households, and Phish has been known to play Hebrew songs in concert. At live shows, many attendees, some wearing T-shirts emblazoned with “Phish” written in Hebrew letters, express feeling something special—even distinctly Jewish—during their performances. As this book shows, Phish is one avenue through which many Jews find cultural and spiritual fulfillment outside the confines of traditional and institutional Jewish life. In effect, Phish fandom and the live Phish experience act as a microcosm through which we see American Jewish religious and cultural life manifest in unique and unexpected spaces.Featuring an interview with Mike Gordon and a collection of fascinating photographs, This Is Your Song Too is an in-depth look at Jewishness in the Phish universe that also provides a deeper understanding of how spirituality, ritual, and identity function in the world of rock and roll.In addition to the editors, the contributors include Evan S. Benn, Dean Budnick, Jacob A. Cohen, Benjamin David, Jessy Dressin, Josh Fleet, Mike Greenhaus, Joshua S. Ladon, Noah Munro Lehrman, Caroline Rothstein, and Isaac Kandall Slone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aRock music fanszUnited States. 0aRock musicxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Rock.2bisacsh  aAmerican Music.  aJeff Holdsworth.  aJewish History.  aJewish Studies.  aJewish identity.  aJon Fishman.  aJonathan Schwartz.  aJudaism.  aMarc Brownstein.  aMike Gordon.  aMusic.  aPage McConnell.  aPhish.  aPopular Culture.  aRachel Loonin Steinerman.  aReligion.  aRock and Roll.  aShirley Halperin.  aThe People of the Helping Friendly Book.  aTrey Anastasio.1 aBenn, Evan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBudnick, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jacob A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavid, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDressin, Jessy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleet, Josh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenhaus, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKroll-Zeldin, Oren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKroll-Zeldin, Oren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLadon, Joshua S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehrman, Noah Munro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothstein, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlone, Isaac Kandall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWerden-Greenfield, Ariella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r